description:
On April 1st, 2014, Kris Kremers and Lisanne Froon, two students in their early twenties, set out on a hike in the jungle near Boquete, Panama. 

Two months later, their mutilated remains were discovered miles off the beaten path. 

Theories range from government cover-ups, foul play, drug cartels, and a deviant tour guide, labeling Kris and Lisanne's case as: The Case of the Dutch Girls.

The case of Kris Kremers and Lisanne Froon remains one of the strangest disappearances in Panamanian history‚Ä¶

comments.text: I've recovered remains that were scavenged, there are unmistakable marks, gouges and scratches. Even river bed or water damage can be seen by the naked eye. Also the pelvic bone is one of the strongest in the body, besides the jaw, it is not common to have the two pieces found separate, it would mean that the leg would have been "scissored" upwards or to the side in a extreme and unnatural angle , tearing the muscle, tissue, with enough force to snap the bone in two. Not even if she had given birth before would the weak point on the pelvis be weak enough for that to just happen. What no one has mentioned here is that there were other bone shards found near the remains of K and L. These bones were never officially identified (if they were, please correct me). Another oddity is how clean the back pack and contents were. River sediment would be found in the bottom of the bag, if it had landed in the river, the fibres acting as a sieve to filter the water out, but keep debris. No mention was made that one of the girls had their medical insurance card in the bag too. Conveniently, one passport, one med card, to identify each of the girls by. The foot in boot was also particularly interesting to me. It was cut clean through. The bone was not broken or shattered, as if from a fall or a stumble down a hill or from a great height. The boot itself was also in good condition. The knots still securely tied, no scuff or scrape marks. I have been lost. Its easy to panic and think just keep going you'll find a way out now. But moving at night is never a good idea. They could have used the flash to try and orientate themselves in the darkness. But this would normally be done by hold the camera up high, so that the flash would allow for as big a panoramic shot as possible. I have no exact cause to this feeling, but I get a sense that yes they were trying to see. But not where they were, rather what was there with them. Or they were shooting blindly in the hopes something could be seen on it later, leaving a photo breadcrumb trail. What I also found odd was that while both cell phones were recovered, there was no mention of personal texts sent that failed or draft messages. If you are in a hopeless situation and you believe you may not make it, it's common to type up messages to your loved ones, so if the devices are found, they are there saved as a draft. They did not try to contact any family members or the consulate either. Which gives an indication into their state of mind - that whatever they were facing, only 911 and the Dutch version thereof could help them. Too many unanswered questions, with blatant inaccuracies. We may never know what happened, but I think we all have a very clear knowledge of the absolute terror and nauseating fear they felt. Knowing what happened won't bring them back, but it would bring closure, and I think that regardless of how horrific the truth is, it is still preferable to the brutal trauma of not knowing. If anyone is still actively pursuing this enquiry, please keep us updated. It is something that has captivated and haunted soo many. My deepest sympathy and condolences to their families and friends.

comments.text:
Questions for the theorists and sleuths:
1.  If they were being pursued by a bad person while going down the backside:  Why did they stop to take pictures?  Why didn't they take pictures of the pursuer (the missing photo is "after" the other trek down photos, not in the middle of the set of going down photos)?
2.  If they were not being pursued by a bad person while going down the backside:  Why would they trek further from home so late in the day, and without food and extra clothing?
3.  The trail going down the backside is very treacherous, why would day hikers not turn around at the first advanced rope bridge as the sun was already setting?
4.  If they simply got lost, why didn't they just turnaround and go back the way they came?
5.  If only one was injured, why didn't the non-injured girl go for rescue?  In other words, why stay in the same place for days without food and extra clothing?   Were both injured?

comments.text:
I just hiked this trail today and it took me about two hours to get from the road to the summit in the pouring rain. It‚Äôs easy to follow the trail after you enter the forrest and the edges where there aren‚Äôt farms are impenetrable jungle. Also, most of the areas that are private land/farms have fences, so I find it extremely unlikely that these girls took a wrong turn. Also, you follow the river valley most of the way to the summit, so finding your way back is fairly easy. Even in the dark it wouldn‚Äôt be impossible.

Even if they did get lost there is plenty of fresh water, so they could easily have survived for days. No way did an animal kill them, nor did they starve to death. The only animal even capable of killing an adult in the jungle and tearing it to pieces is a jaguar. Thinking that one of these cats killed two adults and scattered their body parts all over the place is extremely unlikely. 

If anything natural caused their deaths the most likely thing I would suspect is hypothermia. It does get cold at the top and if they didn‚Äôt have the right clothes it would have been tough at night. I still doubt that together they would have frozen to death.

The only theory that makes sense to me is that somebody killed them, the only question is who?

comments.text: There is absolutely no way that the girls got lost on the Pianista trail.  Photo 509 is the key as it most likely reveals the people responsible for their disappearance, that is obviously why it was erased at a later date with a computer.  The emergency calls after the 1st day and the night time photos are subterfuge.  The emergency calls on the 1st day, April 1, are most likely from the girls, but all after that day are not from them.  For argument's sake, let's say that the girls kept walking past the Mirador on the other side of the continental divide past the small waterfall in photo 508.  If the 1st emergency phone call was at 4:39 PM and the girls reached the Mirador at roughly 1:00 PM, then they would still be walking on the trails for over three hours before the 1st emergency call.  Let's say that they did eventually get lost, then why aren't there any photos of them on the trail after 508? They wouldn't have gotten lost right away, so they would still be walking and enjoying themselves and taking photos.  If you believe in the sequential order of the photos, then they obviously ran into some people right after 508 and 509 is most likely a photo of those people.   They then led them down another path never to be seen again.  If the sequence of the photos was changed, then they most likely returned to the base of the trail and were then intercepted by some guys who convinced them to take a ride with them. comments.text: First of all, the town is called "Boh-KETT-ay", which is standard Spanish pronunciation. There have been a number of YT channels and documentaries that have examined this incident. comments.text:
They we're lost, died in a cave, near the river.. (If you line up all the night pictures, you'll see it's a cave!!)
The bodies had some time to start decomposition, till a flashflood dragged their remains into the river..
This weakened the joints in their bodies, causing their bones to separate. 
Obviously, a bone without shoes around it will decompose much faster than one in a shoe..
It's much harder for insects to help decomposition inside a shoe..
Which explains why the pelvis bone seems more "bleached" (had more sunlight and contact with soil, which contains phosphor..)
Unlike the meat in the shoe, which was protected from it and found UNDERNEATH A TREE IN SHADE!!!
It's also possible Kris died a few days before Lisanne, which would explain why the wrong PIN was used..
Sure, it's reasonable to expect Lisanne to know it, but don't forget she might have been panicked, hungry, and disoriented.. 
The skin is also easy to explain, a layer of skin, can easily dry in the sun causing it to become like leather... or jerky.. 
Obviously, from that moment it's gonna take a looooong time for it to decompose.

A few pieces of information about this case online are also wrong..
If you trace the sources, you'll see that the original sources of some claims, never even made the claim.. 
Like the backpack being in pristine condition, her father said in an interview the bag had drag marks, leaves and dirt..
Which would indicate them falling with the bag, or the bag being in the river..
It also wasn't dry.. nor found under a tree, but just at the riverbank.

The claims they called 77times in later days was claimed to be from RTL late night 1-10-2014..
But if you actually watch it, they don't say that all..
